  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is there really no income requirement for the UAE Freelancer Visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Correct. Unlike the Digital Nomad Visa ($3,500/month threshold), the Freelancer Visa through Free Zones has no income requirement. You pay the annual license fee regardless of how much you earn. This makes it accessible to freelancers at all income levels.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work with UAE-based clients?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. The Freelancer Visa allows you to invoice clients anywhere in the world, including UAE companies. This is a key advantage over the Digital Nomad Visa, which only allows work for foreign employers. You can build a local client base legally.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the difference between Free Zones?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Free Zones differ in cost, location, permitted activities, and prestige. Dubai-based zones (DMCC, Dubai Media City) cost more but provide a Dubai address. Northern Emirates zones (RAKEZ, Ajman) are budget-friendly. Each zone has specific activities they license—check compatibility with your profession.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I bring my family?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Once your freelance visa is active, you can sponsor dependents (spouse, children, and in some cases parents). Each dependent requires additional visa fees and separate health insurance. There's no income threshold for family sponsorship with the freelancer visa.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I really pay zero income tax?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The UAE has no personal income tax. Your freelance income is 100% yours. However, your home country may still have tax obligations—US citizens must file worldwide income regardless of residence. Consult a tax professional about your specific situation.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I open a UAE bank account?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. With your Emirates ID and freelance license, you can open personal and business bank accounts. Popular options include Emirates NBD, Mashreq, ADCB, and digital banks like Liv and Wio. Requirements vary by bank—some require minimum balances or income proof.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The UAE Freelancer Visa offers a compelling package: zero income tax, fast processing (2-4 weeks), no income requirement, and the ability to work with clients worldwide including UAE companies. The Free Zone system is well-established and straightforward.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The trade-offs are cost and climate. Annual fees range from $2,000 (budget Free Zones) to $7,000+ (premium Dubai zones), plus mandatory health insurance. Dubai's cost of living is high. And the summer heat is genuinely brutal—expect to spend June-September indoors or traveling.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      For freelancers earning $5,000+ monthly, the tax savings often exceed all costs combined. At $100,000 annual income, you save $25,000-40,000 in taxes compared to most Western countries. That's a compelling financial case even after accounting for higher living costs and visa fees.
    </p>

